                <fr:title text="Prime spectrum of a distributive lattice">Prime spectrum of a distributive lattice</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  For any distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, we use <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> to denote the poset of prime filters of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. Equivalently, this is the poset of <html:em>models</html:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-2V10/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-2V10</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-2V10/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Local satisfaction relation">Local satisfaction relation</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  For a distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, we define the <html:em>satisfaction relation</html:em> as follows: For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  D]]></fr:tex>, we define
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x \models  a \Leftrightarrow  a \in  x. ]]></fr:tex>
  In other words, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \models  a]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a = 1]]></fr:tex> in the <fr:link href="/idem-comm-IHKN/" title="Local algebra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-IHKN/" display-uri="idem-comm-IHKN" type="local">local algebra</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/x]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-59IF/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-59IF</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-59IF/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Set-level duality between spectra and algebra">Set-level duality between spectra and algebra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : D \to  E]]></fr:tex> between distributive lattices:
  <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is injective iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} E \twoheadrightarrow  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is surjective.</html:li>
    <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is surjective iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} E \subseteq  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is a full subposet.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  The first statement is an easy consequence of completeness. For the second statement, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}]]></fr:tex> takes regular epis in <html:strong>DL</html:strong> to regular monos in <html:strong>Pos</html:strong>, thus the only if direction holds. For the if direction, take a map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : D \to  E]]></fr:tex>, we can factor it as a surjection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q : D \twoheadrightarrow  E']]></fr:tex> followed by an injection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i : E' \rightarrowtail  E]]></fr:tex>. This induces a factorisation on posets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q : \operatorname {Spec} E' \to  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, a regular mono, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i : \operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} E']]></fr:tex>, which is surjective by (1). Hence, if the composite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[iq]]></fr:tex> is a regular mono, so is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism. This way, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> must be a quotient.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-CU42/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-CU42</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-CU42/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Zariski topology">Zariski topology</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  The <html:em>Zariski topology</html:em> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is induced by a basis <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex> for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  D]]></fr:tex>,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ O_p := \{x\in  \operatorname {Spec} D\mid p \in  x\}. ]]></fr:tex>
  It is easy to verify that
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ O_1 = \operatorname {Spec} D, \quad  O_0 = \emptyset , \quad  O_{p \wedge  q} = O_p \cap  O_q, \quad  O_{p \vee  q} = O_p \cup  O_q,]]></fr:tex>
  thus this indeed forms a basis.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-HLDT</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-HLDT/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Frame of opens of spectra">Frame of opens of spectra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  There is a bijection of frame of opens of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> with the frame <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Idl}(D)]]></fr:tex> of ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. For any ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, the open subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_I]]></fr:tex> it corresponds to is
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ O_I := \{x\in \operatorname {Spec} D\mid \exists  p \in  I.\  x \models  p\} = \bigcup _{p\in  I}O_p. ]]></fr:tex></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  For simplicity, we construct a dual equivalence between closed sets and ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. By construction, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_p]]></fr:tex> be the complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex>, then the closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> corresponding to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is given by 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ C_I = \overline {O_I} = \bigcap _{p\in  I}C_p. ]]></fr:tex>
  On the other hand, given any closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> we construct an ideal
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ I_C := \{p\in  D\mid \forall  x\in  C.\ x \not \models  p\}. ]]></fr:tex>
  Verification is routine.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-QVV9/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-QVV9</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-QVV9/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Subspace of pro-open quotients">Subspace of pro-open quotients</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  For a filter <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, via <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W57Q/" title="Prime ideals of pro-open quotient" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" /></fr:link> the spectrum <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/F]]></fr:tex> can be naturally seen as a subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, which is given by 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} D/F = \{x\in \operatorname {Spec} D\mid \forall  a \in  F.\  x \models  a\} = \bigcap _{a\in  F}O_a, ]]></fr:tex>
  This subspace will be <html:em>upward closed</html:em>, but in general may <html:em>fail</html:em> to be open in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, since it is an infinite intersection of basic opens. This is the reason why we call quotients of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \twoheadrightarrow  D/F]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/idem-comm-0002/" title="Pro-open quotients" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-0002/" display-uri="idem-comm-0002" type="local">pro-open</fr:link>, rather than <html:em>open</html:em>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-FMRA/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-FMRA</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-FMRA/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Closed subspace of closed quotient">Closed subspace of closed quotient</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Dually, for an ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, let us write the quotient obtained by taking all elements in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \twoheadrightarrow  \operatorname {Spec} I/D]]></fr:tex>. By the dual form of <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W57Q/" title="Prime ideals of pro-open quotient" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" /></fr:link>, again we have a natural subspace <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} I/D \subseteq  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, which can be seen as 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} I/D = \{x\in \operatorname {Spec} D\mid \forall  a \in  I.\  x \not \models  a\} = \bigcap _{a\in  I}C_a = C_I. ]]></fr:tex>
  Thus, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} I/D]]></fr:tex> will indeed be <html:em>closed</html:em> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, hence we refer to quotients of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I/D]]></fr:tex> as <html:em>closed quotients</html:em>. This also implies that a subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is closed iff it is downward closed.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W1VU/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-W1VU</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-W1VU/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Irreducible closed subsets of spectra">Irreducible closed subsets of spectra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Under the isomorphism in <fr:link href="/idem-comm-HLDT/" title="Frame of opens of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" /></fr:link>, a closed subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> corresponding to an ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/topl-0001/" title="Irreducible space" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-0001/" display-uri="topl-0001" type="local">irreducible</fr:link> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is a prime ideal.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> is irreducible. If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \wedge  q \in  I]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I \subseteq  C_{p \wedge  q} = C_p \cup  C_q]]></fr:tex>. By irreducibility, either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  I]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in  I]]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is a prime ideal. 
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    On the other hand, suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is prime. If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> is not irreducible, then we can find ideals <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J,K]]></fr:tex> that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I \subseteq  C_J \cup  C_K = C_{J \cap  K}]]></fr:tex>, or equivalently <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J \cap  K \subseteq  I]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J \not \subseteq  I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K \not \subseteq  I]]></fr:tex>. This way, pick <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  J-I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in  K-I]]></fr:tex>, we get <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \wedge  q\in  I]]></fr:tex> but <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \not \in  I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\not \in  I]]></fr:tex>, contradictory. Hence, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> must be irreducible.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-EA6S/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-EA6S</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-EA6S/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Spectra are spectral spaces">Spectra are spectral spaces</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">spectral</fr:link>. This gives us a functor
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} : \mathbf {DL}^{\mathrm {op}} \to  \mathbf {Spec} ]]></fr:tex>
  from distributive lattices to spectral spaces.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    Notice that we have a homeomorphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ O_p \cong  \operatorname {Spec} D/p, ]]></fr:tex>
    where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex> is viewed as an open subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>. Hence, we only need to show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is compact and sober for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_p]]></fr:tex> be the complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  D]]></fr:tex>, and suppose we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \bigcap _{i\in  I}C_{p_i} = \emptyset . ]]></fr:tex>
    This means that the family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p_i\}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> is inconsistent, thus by compactness, finitely many of them is already inconsistent. Thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is compact, and compact opens in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> are all of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  D]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    To show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/topl-FII1/" title="Sober spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-FII1/" display-uri="topl-FII1" type="local">sober</fr:link>, by <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W1VU/" title="Irreducible closed subsets of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W1VU/" display-uri="idem-comm-W1VU" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W1VU/" display-uri="idem-comm-W1VU" /></fr:link> any irreducible closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> corresponds to some prime ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>. This way, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> be the complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>. We now have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I = \overline {\{x\}}]]></fr:tex>, because
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x \not \in  O_p \Leftrightarrow  x \in  C_p \Leftrightarrow  x \not \models  p \Leftrightarrow  p \in  I. ]]></fr:tex>
    Thus we indeed have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I = \bigcap _{p\in  I}C_p = \bigcap _{x\not \in  O_p}C_p = \overline {\{x\}}]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    Finally to show a map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : D \to  E]]></fr:tex> induces a continuous map
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} f : \operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} D, ]]></fr:tex>
    it suffices to note that, set-theoretically, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} fx = f^{-1} x]]></fr:tex>, which is a prime filter in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. Now we have 
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ (\operatorname {Spec} f)^{-1}(O_a) = O_{fa} ]]></fr:tex>
    for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \in  D]]></fr:tex>, hence this is a spectral map.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>8</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-BA70/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-BA70</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-BA70/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Duality between distributive lattices and spectral spaces">Duality between distributive lattices and spectral spaces</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  In fact, the functor in <fr:link href="/idem-comm-EA6S/" title="Spectra are spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-EA6S/" display-uri="idem-comm-EA6S" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-EA6S/" display-uri="idem-comm-EA6S" /></fr:link> is an equivalence.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-WKAD/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-WKAD</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-WKAD/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Spectra as classifying spaces">Spectra as classifying spaces</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  The space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> classifies the prime filters of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> in the following sense: For any topos <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {X}]]></fr:tex>, we have
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathbf {Topoi}(\mathcal {X},\operatorname {Spec} D) \simeq  \mathbf {DL}(D,\mathrm {Sub}_{\mathcal {X}}(1)). ]]></fr:tex></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  By <fr:link href="/idem-comm-HLDT/" title="Frame of opens of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" /></fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> as a frame is the coherent locale <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Idl}(D)]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. Thus we indeed have
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathbf {Topoi}(\mathcal {X},\operatorname {Spec} D) \simeq  \mathbf {Frm}(\mathrm {Idl}(D),\mathrm {Sub}_{\mathcal {X}}(1)) \simeq  \mathbf {DL}(D,\mathrm {Sub}_{\mathcal {X}}(1)). ]]></fr:tex>
  In particular, when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {X}]]></fr:tex> is two-valued, these are prime filters of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-ZATP/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-ZATP</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-ZATP/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Prime spectra of free distributive lattices">Prime spectra of free distributive lattices</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  For any poset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, it generates a free distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2[I]]]></fr:tex>. When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is finite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2[I]]]></fr:tex> is a Heyting algebra, but it will never be Boolean expect when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is empty. The spectrum
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} 2[I] \cong  \mathbf {Pos}(I,2) \cong  \mathcal {U}(I), ]]></fr:tex>
  is the upward closed subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>. 
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-BF49/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-BF49</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-BF49/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Prime spectra of Boolean algebras">Prime spectra of Boolean algebras</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Let us consider a Boolean algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} B]]></fr:tex> is the Stone space associated to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>. In particular, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {B}[x]]]></fr:tex> is the free Boolean algebra generated by one element, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {B}[x] \cong  2]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> is the discrete set.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-2XKS/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-2XKS</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-2XKS/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Prime spectra of linear lattices">Prime spectra of linear lattices</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  For a bounded linear order <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>, which is a Heyting algebra, prime filters are the upward closed subsets containing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> but not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex>,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} L \cong  \mathcal {U}_+(L). ]]></fr:tex>
  The topology on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {U}_+(L)]]></fr:tex> is generated by the following basis for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  L]]></fr:tex>,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ O_p = \{U\in \mathcal {U}_+(L)\mid p \in  U\}. ]]></fr:tex>
  For instance, for the poset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {\omega }]]></fr:tex>, its spectral space is simply <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {\omega }^{\mathrm {op}}]]></fr:tex> with the Alexandroff topology,
  
  
  <html:figure><fr:resource hash="cd94a92757930b493ba04cb20dd705ac"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/cd94a92757930b493ba04cb20dd705ac.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
  \begin {tikzcd}
    {\overline {\omega }} && {\mathrm {Spec}\ \overline {\omega }} \\
    \bullet  && \bullet  \\
    \vdots  && \bullet  \\
    \bullet  && \vdots  \\
    \bullet  && \bullet 
    \arrow [from=3-1, to=2-1]
    \arrow [from=3-3, to=2-3]
    \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-1]
    \arrow [from=4-3, to=3-3]
    \arrow [from=5-1, to=4-1]
    \arrow [from=5-3, to=4-3]
  \end {tikzcd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>9</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-B6WQ/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-B6WQ</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/idem-comm-B6WQ/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Prime spectrums from commutative rings">Prime spectrums from commutative rings</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  For any commutative ring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>, recall the classical Zariski spectrum <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} R]]></fr:tex> has points <html:em>prime ideals</html:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. We will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D[R]]]></fr:tex> for the distributive lattice of compact opens of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} R]]></fr:tex>, and there is a natural map
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ R \to  D[R] ]]></fr:tex>
  sending <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \in  R]]></fr:tex> to the compact open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_f := \{x\in \operatorname {Spec} R\mid  f \not \in  x \}]]></fr:tex>. This is a <html:em>monoid morphism</html:em>, which takes finite products in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> to intersection in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D[R]]]></fr:tex>. Furthermore, we know that they produce the same Zariski spectra,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} R \cong  \operatorname {Spec} D[R] ]]></fr:tex>
  Hence, sometimes we will also generate prime spectra directly from commutative rings.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
  For instance, this gives us the usual affine complex line 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} \mathbb {C}[x] \cong  \mathbb {C} \cup  \{\infty \}, ]]></fr:tex>
  where open sets are either empty, or a cofinite subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> together with the generic point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\infty ]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
